3< /rating>
< Review>
Second time at a Loving Hut. The first time was in the Sunset in SF, which was great. We tried the hot dog (overpriced, tiny, and nothing special), the sesame bites (which were really soft and different from other sesame bites I have had, which normally mimic chicken rather than beef, in a sauce that was more gelatinous than sauce-ey), and, thankfully much better than the rest, the pesto grill (which was very good, would buy again).

I would probably not bring my non-vegan friends here for their first vegan restaurant, as the menu seems to be a hit or miss compared to other options in the area.<//Review>

<user>100544028757514916908<//user><rating>4< /rating><Pictures>None</Pictures><Name>M D<//Name>< text>
A vegan option at Oakridge Mall is very welcome, and I usually enjoy the "meatless" meats offered. I tried the Vermicelli Delicacy and Sesame Bites. The flavor of the Sesame Bites was unimpressive to me, I wouldn't get it again, but the Vermicelli I would get again.

The food quality here is just average in comparison to its non-vegan versions, as well as other vegan eateries I've tried. If the prices reflected the quality of food more I would give them 4 stars, but at $5 for an appetizer, and about $9 for some very average vegan dishes, I feel like its a bit too expensive.

But I still like the Loving Hut and will be back! I intend to try some of the other items which I see are more popular.<//text>

< text>
Update to my review. Received notification that they now accept recycling of batteries, motor oil, and 3 big trash pick-ups a year. Great news!

Waiting for the day that Pleasanton switches to an actual garabg company like waste management. Ever since moving to Pleasanton, trash service has been pathetic. They will not pick up oil to recycle, no big trash day. Horrible trash pick up service. Cans are knocked down, and/or pieces of trash always blown into front yard. I have yet to figure any positive on why Pleasanton has its own trash service opposed to a public company like other cities. But hey, maybe it makes the city wonder why people throw stuff in cans they shouldn't, or dump stuff they shouldn't.. because the trash service blows.</text>

<user>102475983201576037933<//user><rate>3</rate>< Review>
the room, across from the vineyards, with a private hot tub, was very nice, with the exception of the fact that we had to call the front desk three (3!) times asking for the cleaning team to come back - there were serious issues with the cleanliness of the room that they would not catch even though they were obvious, and we described them in detail.

We don't know if it was because of them having less resources due to COVID, or because there was a large wedding on site that weekend, but we do know that, for the price we paid and the quality we expected, one call to complain about the cleanliness of the room was one call too many... To make it worse, the first two times we called the front desk we heard them say "oh, we are sorry and we are going to send someone to take care of those "details"". To be clear, the issues we found were **not** "details" - a dead bug on the frame atop the bed is not a "detail", lint on multiple corners of the room are not "details", the frame of the magnifying glass in the bathroom is not a "detail", dirt behind the toilet is definitely not a detail.

Unfortunately, we had this issue for two days (when we stayed at the hotel for 2.5 days), so our overall experience was much less than what we would have liked/expected - Consider this a 2.5 stars review< /Review>

<username>Amogh Mundhekar<//username><Date>1621607706142< /Date><Rating>1< /Rating>< review>
Unfortunately our stay was terribly disappointing. We booked a $550 room  based on the 3D tour listed on the harvest inn website which was supposed to have a patio and a spa hot tub. However when we checked in, it was truly disappointing to see that the representation on the website was completely a lie and misleading. The actual room was a claustrophobic unit with no patio, no spa tub and no sunlight. We specifically chose Harvest inn because of this room, and at such a high price it was a terrible disappointment. The lady at the counter was nice enough to offer us a spot discount or a cancelation option, but it was too late for us to go find a different place.<//review>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
There are lots of places to stay in wine country and I have to admit, there are several I haven‚Äôt stayed at but the Harvest Inn is one that you have to give a try. The grounds are a well manicured natural rustic look with beautiful art, sculptures, ponds and fountains throughout. Two pools and hot tubs (one adults only üëçüèº), restaurant, full bar, spa, cigar bar and transportation right at your fingertips. Seriously what else could you need for a fantastic getaway.
The main thing that stands out are the incredible staff! Everyone we encountered was extremely helpful and genuinely courteous, ensuring a delightful stay. All of this at a very reasonable price, you just can‚Äôt go wrong. Thank you for a much needed remarkable stay.< /Review>

<rate>1<//rate>< Review>
At first glance it's a great place.
I stayed here while on a business trip and could not believe how unhelpful, unprofessional and downright rude the staff is.
There was a major ant  infestation in my restroom. I notified the management informed them of the problem and they said they would get right on it. Three phone calls and three hours later they sent to bus boys to handle the problem. The two came armed with Windex in a spray bottle and a small propane torch in hand. Now I am no exterminator but I do know that was a strange combination to handle an ant problem. After 30 minutes of the two working at the ant problem I poked my head in the bathroom door and they were burning the ants with the propane torch. Then they proceeded to fill all the cracks in the tile floor with toilet paper in hopes that would keep the ants out.
I'm Very disappointed in the place. I believe for the price they're charging I could have got a lot better.<//Review>

<name>Hotels.com reviewer<//name><response>None<//response><gmap_id>0x808450cfb3c6de79:0x997b71cfa75c0721<//gmap_id><Rate>None</Rate><UserId.>None< /UserId.><Review>We took our first family trip and our stay at harvest inn was great. The grounds and buildings are beautiful, the staff is great and all was very clean. Having never been to Napa this made a great first impression. The rooms were nice and spacious and the pool was never crowded</Review><Pics>None</Pics><time>1597536000000< /time></record>
</dataset><record>
< Review>
The Harvest Inn is located right outside downtown St. Helena and amongst numerous wineries. The staff is welcoming with enthusiastic dispositions; you can tell they try to make each guest's visit personal, taking care to remember names.

They have a pool and hot tub, heated well and good for a morning dip. The Harvest Inn rooms offer spacious accommodations set in a quaint courtyard. And who needs a pool with these even more spacious bathtubs. And they are pet friendly!

The food is excellent, locally sourced and prepared with sublime flavor combinations. We were well taken care of.

As for the robes, I'm not much of a robe wearer but robes say a lot about a place so I always have to have a feel. For those robe wearers out there these have top marks. Plush and soft, I was definitely living in mine.

**BEST YET they were very accommodating towards evacuees with animals. During this year's fires in August 2020 the animal fee was waived which was an immense help and relief.**

My only negative criticism is the tiny fridge. It didn't pose much of a problem but it took some rearranging and stacking to fit everything. So for those who like to keep snacks drinks or leftovers you might want to reconsider.

And perhaps an investment in better coffee machines for the rooms.  Keurigs are a thing of the past.  An invention for easy subpar coffee that creates too much waste.</Review>

< review>
My boyfriend and I stayed at the Harvest Inn for my birthday weekend in the Napa Valley. The entire hotel is cottage-style rooms that has a much more home-y feel, rather than a large hotel with 30+ floors. All of the staff was extremely welcoming and helpful, especially when checking in and finding your room.

Our room backed up to the vineyard behind the hotel, so the views were amazing! Every vineyard view room has a hot tub on the back patio which was a great added touch.

We couldn't have been happier at this hotel and will definitely be back!</review>

< Text>
Harvest Inn. Is nice place to stay in St. helena about 17 miles up north from Napa. My wife and I spend 6 days at Harvest inn this December. Weather is chilly at St. helena. Also it‚Äôs walking distance to like 4 wineries for wine tasting and also there lots of small mom and pops shop to buy clothing and food. All the shops are pretty expensive. Only complain I have is for the money we spend they should have given us free breakfast. I would do research prior to booking at st helena again and would not stay longer than a weekend. Some of the positive things at Harvest Inn was free parking, free WiFi and our package came with a small wine bottle. It was nice place to stay but will not stay longer than weekend and it‚Äôs Mainentence is nice and clean.< /Text>

<Pics>None<//Pics>< review>
The pictures online didn't leave me thinking this would be an amazing hotel.   I found staying at the Harvest Inn to be an excellent experience.   The room and bed very nice.   Our room had a view of the adjoining Vineyard and hills behind and large fireplace.

I found all of the staff to be very attentive, friendly,  and a general pleasure to interact with.   I would particularly like to comment that the concierge Joshua is a significant asset.   He was very helpful and understanding of our tastes and interests.

The staff at the restaurant were also impressive.   They not only took the time to remember us from one day to the next, but went the next step to recall how we liked to sit next to each other.

The cleaning staff kept the room clean, stocked,  and in order throughout our stay.

All in all a big thanks to the Harvest Inn team for making our stay special and memorable.<//review>

< Review>
BEWARE, we had a one night reservation for 10/31/19. Uncontrolled fires were burning in Sonoma and surrounding areas, Highway 101 and other major roads were closed causing serious traffic congestion, etc. I called early 10/28 to cancel, took me more than once to get through due to busy or down circuits. I was told I was "outside the cancellation period" therefore my deposit would be forfeited. I explained that we couldn't reach them due to the fires and congestion between us and them; they agreed to hold the deposit for a future visit to be used within one year. I sent an email to the Manager, Nathan Davis on 11/25 explaining the situation and asking him to consider a refund; no response. I thought perhaps Dr Davis did not receive my email so I sent him a registered letter on 12/5 and it was received and signed for on 12/9; again, not even the courtesy of a response. We cancelled all of the reservations we had made for hotels, dinners, wine tastings, spa treatments, well over 20 in total and each and every place graciously honored our cancellation without hesitation or penalty except for Harvest Inn. I guess Harvest Inn needs my $218.30 deposit more than I do and doesn't care about me being a guest in the future.<//Review>

<username>Nikki Parks-Comer<//username><Date>1521576046119<//Date><rate>5< /rate>< Text>
My husband and I both somewhat low-key people and we were looking for somewhere to stay that had a bit of a relaxed vibe. This hotel couldn't have been more perfect. We stayed in one of the spa vineyard view rooms and it was very much like a quaint cottage to me. Breakfast was scrambled eggs, potatoes, bacon, fresh fruit, yogurt and oatmeal served buffet style in the hotel's on location restaurant. It was very relaxed and quite good.
They have a car available to drive you to locations within St. Helena and that worked pretty well for us when we had a few reservations that we preferred not to drive ourselves.
It is pretty centrally located and that made it easy to get from vineyard to vineyard in a reasonable amount of time.
We loved staying here and plan on returning. It was one of the best experiences we have ever had.< /Text>

< review>
There's so much to like about this place... the location, the completely redone and beautiful main common areas, and the service, which is world class.   The restaurant is delicious and fits in perfectly with the St. Helena hyper local farm-fresh to table concepts throughout the area.

Parking was free and always easy. They also do a pretty good breakfast Continental style in the restaurant which is complementary to every hotel guest.  The Hook-Up is they will deliver exactly what you want to your room for five bucks (tip), just fill out the card provided in room.

I would like to remind everyone that it is a older property that has been re-done.  They did spend a considerable amount of money getting the rooms up to five-star standards today.

That being said, I had a room facing the highway on the ground floor and the noise from the street, coupled with the people walking up and down the stairs (banging suitcases etc) every morning didn't typify a five star experience for me.< /review>

< Name>
Travelocity reviewer</Name>
<Text>The Harvest Inn is a well-located small inn close to wineries and good restaurants. I liked the curb-side check in when I pulled up. I was a bit early so my room wasnt ready but waited in the comfortable lounges on the deck and enjoyed a light lunch from the excellent restaurant. Break fast is included with the room and was delicious with a choice of hot items (bacon is fabulous) and pastries. I could have used more fruit options at breakfast but that a minor point. I had a fountain room and it was comfortable with a small balcony (ask for a second story room, if possible). Large-ish room with nice soaking tub and separate shower. I was in Napa for a conference not as a tourist so didnt spend much time at the pool or spa. The pool was small but nice. It was over 100 degrees so was too hot to sit out for too long even under an umbrella. Pool included separate hot tub area.</Text>< response>

<text>Funny story - I was staying here for the night after my bestie's wedding, which took place up the road. The guy who officiated the wedding celebrated a little too much and couldn't remember where he was staying. The friendly night crew at Harvest Inn were so sweet. They called around to a few local hotels to see if he was registered anywhere close. (Mind you, this was close to 2 am). In the end, we could never find out where my drunk friend was staying, so the night staff gave me some extra bedding to put him on a pull out bed in my room. They were so friendly and helpful that I would love to rate Harvest Inn way above 5 stars!

The rooms are cozy with huge bathrooms and baths that I could live in for days. The area around the Inn is also beautiful - almost like a little childhood storybook. I even went running early in the morning alongside lovely vineyards, and finished my run with a healthy complementary breakfast - complete with a mimosa.

Definitely going back to the Inn soon!<//text><pics>None< /pics>< response>

<name>Monica Marks</name>< text>
They didn't check for the door hanger for my breakfast order, so no breakfast. I had it out on the door by 1am at latest. Noted that it needed to be on the door by 5am.  So that was pretty lame.

This place is pricey, but super quaint and quiet. The rotating outdoor art (sculpture garden) is cool.

Everything there and in town shuts down at 10pm, so make sure you have any snacks or beverages you may want to have between 10pm and 7am arranged/acquired. Or you'll be sorry!</text>

The Harvest Inn was our choice for 25th anniversary trip to Napa - and did not disappoint.   We stayed in one of the Spa Vineyard rooms overlooking the vineyard on the back side of the property, so didn't really experience any road noise.  While it is something of a premium rate, the room was spacious and comfortable and exactly what we were looking for to visit.  About a mile from the center of St. Helena and no more then a 20 minute drive to just about any of the Napa wineries we visited - from Spring Mountain to Del Dotto Caverns (using a driver of course!).   The staff was extremely helpful with any request we made.  A great experience.< /review>

<Text>Spent 2 nights here with friends for a 50th birthday celebration the first weekend of November . The inn was nice, but nothing exceptional for what we paid. Our room was standard, with a queen bed, desk and single chair. Really? Not even 2 chairs?  Bathroom was nice and appeared updated. We travel quite a bit, and the night before arriving at the Harvest Inn we stayed in San Francisco at a charming inn, which featured a complimentary wine and cheese reception, fire pit, and a continental breakfast for half of what we paid at Harvest inn. Breakfast was fine, food ran out quickly and it was quite busy. Although complimentary, tips are ‚Äòsuggested‚Äô at breakfast, even though guests refill their own drinks, etc. I  think the rooms did not live up to the hype/photos on the website. No one to greet you upon arrival, the service at check-in was no better than you would get at a Courtyard Marriott-friendly but nothing special for this price point. In addition, we were told at check in that there is two bottles of water, one bottle of orange juice (not sure what you do if there is two of you wanting juice) and a ‚Äúbottle‚Äù of wine. Well there was no wine in the room so I called up to the front desk to let them know and I was told a ‚Äúbottle‚Äù of wine would be sent up.

The ‚Äúbottle‚Äù was Whitehall and it was enough to maybe get two glasses out it. This probably cost the hotel $5 to buy...maybe nothing...done as marketing. To put this into context, a 750ML of the same Whitehall wine that gives you six servings is $30.

Harvest Table for breakfast was a disappointment. It was a buffet and worst part about it was a terrible buffet.

Went to ck our after three night. When I booked via their website you get a $40 credit toward the restaurant. Well we decided to use that for the buffet but were told you can only use it for lunch or dinner; of course...you spend much more during those time. How trivial for a ‚Äú4 Star‚Äù establishment.

We come to Napa at once least once a year; we got married here. We had driven by the Harvest Inn many times and thought to try it out...i was expecting an amazing experience...not so much< /Review>

My wife and I booked a spa package vineyard view king room for our honeymoon. The property was beautiful and the service was good with the exception of housekeeping not providing us with new shampoo and soap. The spa package is deceiving. The room rate for the same room we stayed in was $499/night and the spa package claims you get a spa credit of $200 but what they dont tell you is they uncharge you one night of your stay an additional $150 for the room. The reality is you dont get a $200 spa credit, you end up with a $50 spa credit bc they add an additional $150 to your room rate for one night. <Time>1402693538086<//Time><rating>1<//rating><Review>DO NOT STAY HERE!!!  If I could give NO STARS, I would.  My wife and I had a terrific weekend in Napa last weekend (really only had one day) bur stayed at Harvest Inn on Saturday night.  First thing I would note is that if this property where anywhere but Napa you wouldn't expect to pay more than $89/nt (maybe $120 for a room with a hot tub).  Not the $785 that we paid.  I understand that some would call it quaint but I would call it dated!  The lodge is OK but "wine bar" is inadequate compared to what is available in the area.

So for the price, since you don't get great physical amenities you would think they would make it up in service.  Not at all!!  Firstly, they advertise an available driver into St. Helena .  We tried to schedule a ride for dinner that night and they told us that they only the one driver and that he was booked for the whole evening so don't expect that convenience.

The biggest issue was that at 4:00am, a loud alarm (not fire alarm) started sounding near our room and woke my wife and me.  We waited for 20 minutes and then called the front desk and asked to have someone check on it.  The woman at the front desk told me that she was the only person working but that she would check on it (I will avoid a discussion about an alleged "high-end" facility having only one person on staff for that number units).  We waited 40 minutes and the alarm did not stop.  I finally left our room and searched for the source.  It ended up being and overheating alarm in a mechanical room next to the back of our unit.  I called the front desk and told her.  She said she had walked over by our unit and didn't hear anything (which meant that she hadn't been there).  I told her that I had located the source and then she met me at the mechanical room and was finally able to shut off the alarm.  It was 5:30am at this point.

The worst part is that I mentioned it when I checked out and the person at the desk said that there was not note of the incident but that she would inform the Manager (Kevin) and have him call me.  It has now been a week and I've left 3 messages for Kevin and have not received a return call.  Unacceptable!  I travel quite a bit and have had better service at low end motels in small towns than we received here.</Review><Pics>None< /Pics>< response>

<userid>116834132493836900328< /userid><name>Aggie Zau</name>< Time>

5< /Rating>
< text>
I had my wedding here at the Harvest Inn on May 15, 2021. We had to move our wedding twice due to the pandemic. I could not be more thankful for the team at the Harvest Inn-- Steve Gaebe, Mimi VanDyk and Ashley Smith.

Steve: Throughout both of the movement of my dates, Steve was on hand to communicate which dates were still available for the venue on same day so I could align the movement of the dates with my wedding planner and vendors. He answered my calls regarding the COVID guidelines in Napa county and swiftly introduced me to MiMi, Director or Catering, when she returned to the hotel.

MiMi: There are no words to describe how hard this woman worked. Mimi is genuinely one of the most caring people working in this industry and really makes sure your day is special. Because my wedding was less than a month away upon her returning to work, we had a bit of catching up to do. She was always responsive of my numerous texts and phone calls. My husband and I are super conservative on safety etiquette, making sure a vaccinated server is on hand to serve the guests(nothing family style) and all the food and cocktails were picked according to plan(it's been a while since we all went out!). Her biggest strength is her creativity, regarding my lounge night since we cancelled indoor dancing-- building it out on the Vineyard Terrace as to not disturb the surrounding guests.

Ashley Smith: Thank you for arranging all my room bookings for me and the bridal party. We tried to fill as many rooms as possible!
The Harvest Inn is gorgeous with its redwood trees, vineyards, brick walkways, manicured lawns, and rose bushes. The fountain is so elegant. It is a pet friendly hotel without the pretentious attitude. They even allowed my friend, who made my wedding cake, in the kitchen and gave her some space to put it together. The food and drinks at my wedding were very memorable according to our guests. They were so delicious across all our guests with various dietary restrictions.

We can't imagine celebrating anywhere else and are super excited to come back to celebrate our anniversaries.< /text>

<Review>(Translated by Google) I stayed for one night when I visited the wineries in Napa.

Located in the heart of Napa, St. Helena, along the main street, the location is great.
There are many popular restaurants and shops as well as wineries in St. Helena.

This is one of the best hotels to stay in after a half day sightseeing from San Francisco to Napa. Whether you go north to Calistoga the next day or return to San Francisco, it's easy to make a schedule.

Also, there is a vineyard adjacent to the hotel, so it is nice to take a walk in the early morning.

<review>Das Harvest Inn ist ein wunderschoenes, gepflegtes Hotel mit (fast) allem Komfort am Ortseingang von Saint Helena in der Naehe von grossen und traditionsreichen Weinguetern. Wer nichts gegen einen kleinen Spaziergang (vielleicht 15 Minuten bis zur Ortsmitte) oder eine Fahrt mit dem Auto hat, wird sich hier wohlfuehlen. Der Kamin im Zimmer schafft eine romantische Atmosphaere. In besonders guter Erinnerung haben wir das reichhaltige Fruehstuecksbuffet, das in einem Raum mit Blick auf die Weinberge serviert wird und im Preis inbegriffen war. Letzteres ist ja sehr selten in den USA. Inklusive war auch der Internetzugang in unserem Zimmer sowie eine Flasche Weisswein. Den Jacuzzi haben wir nicht benutzt und koennen daher keine Aussage hierzu treffen. Der Service ist auf hoechstem Niveau. Der Concierge hat stets gute Empfehlungen fuer Aktivitaeten und Restaurants gegeben. Sollten wir noch einmal ins Napa Valley reisen, dann kommen wir bestimmt wieder nach Saint Helena und ins Harvest Inn!< /review><rating>None<//rating>< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>

< text>
Food was OK, services was responsive and attentive. Nice atmosphere . I'm giving it a low grade because I feel it was very over priced for the product. Chair were hardwood with no padding ( uncomfortable after a bit ). We were told the special was $18 , them billed at $26 (the average cost of most items)  and waitress said im sorry, i was wrong, but did not have the authority to correct her mistake. The meals were were high dollar and a salad was $6 extra, a small cup of soup was $5, a glass of house chardonnay was $8.  I ordered the Basil tomato soup that again tasted ok but nothing special. Their custom drinks they really push and  were good but very small proportion and $10. We drove to Hilmar to try this restaurant based on the Surla name, but do not feel the exceptional meals were served to support the exceptional prices. I will give them a couple years to mature and if they still are around, try them again. Bottom line, I would spend my $150 elsewhere when looking for a better than average experience<//text>

Super enjoyable experience! Outdoor dining is definitely the way to go with besitos. I loved the ambiance and the brick wall vibes. As for the food, I really enjoyed the new york steak special and the server was flexible with my substitutions as well. My friend got the waffle and I could smell it from where I was sitting ü§§ Overall, I recommend this place if you're looking for a cute brunch spot with good food and great service! For anyone coming here during covid, people were well spread out and I felt safe</Review>

< review>
Time for an awesome review- I had never been to BESITOS before and could not be more pleased. The food was top notch- like worthy of a michellin star level. I got the chicken and waffles and was blown away. The batter for the chicken was the best I've ever had and the waffles were the perfect consistency and tasted like heaven. While ordering, the chef overheard me mention how much I love churros so he brought me out a churros waffle with ice cream just to say thanks you for having stopped in. That level of service and quality is few and far between. I could not recommend a place more than here. I promise it is worth checking out.< /review>

< Review>
I went into the store with my 2 year old stepson to get us both a new pair of vans. My stepson started getting restless after we found his shoes and I was just about to give up on finding a pair for myself. Jose, one of the vans sales associates, came over with colored pencils and a coloring sheet to help distract my son while I tried on a couple pairs of shoes. Jose even took the time to color with him and helped me carry our shoes to the counter once we were ready to checkout. Jose and the other vans sales associates made what could have been a stressful shopping trip into a great experience. I will definitely be going back when we are looking for new shoes!</Review>

<user_id>110959983314545896903< /user_id><name>Nick Chin<//name><date>1567462508276< /date>< Rating>
1</Rating>
<Text>Like paying for a Safari Ride to LAX.  Late, no A.C. and buses so bumpy it‚Äôs a surprise they passed inspection.

While definitely an affordable way to get to Downtown LA to LAX, riders beware you get what you pay for.

I took this bus from the Hollywood stop to LAX to close out a 4 day trip to LA. The bus was 10mims late and there was a driver swap in the middle of the ride. Definitely don‚Äôt rely on this if you‚Äôre in a rush.

The worse part of the ride was the 95 degree heat and the lack of a AC or a decent fan on the bus. The windows only opened about 3 inches which was not nearly enough to let in even the slightest breeze.

The bus also had absolutely no suspension. Multiple times I was thrown out of my seat and my luggage was launched into the neighboring aisle even on perfectly smooth roads. There is also no luggage storage whatsoever so you are left having to straddle your luggage between your legs if the bus happens to be crowded.

By the time I arrived to LAX, my shirt was soaked through and I was nauseated from the ride. If you have the time, you're better off taking cheaper and more comfortable ride via the LA Metro.<//Text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Resp>
None</Resp>

< text>
$8 credit card, or TAP card. 5:15am-7:15pm Shuttle comes every hour. Come 10min early before time. Takes only 30min to lax if you take the 1st 5:15am shuttle bus. Alot cheaper than taking uber or lyft. Load your luggage, grab your seat, pay the driver and tell her/him your terminal drop. The heater is on for very cold mornings. Get ready for a bumpy ride!!!! Without exaggerating It has zero shocks, meaning every tiny bump makes myself and the 30 other passengers jumping out of our seats. < Text>

The driver was late getting there but actually worked in my favor. It is a smaller shuttle than the others and didnt have Hollywood displayed like the one going to Union. <userid>105536843127229431886<//userid><name>Brendan<//name>< time>
1618712979836</time>
<rate>4<//rate>< text>
Great Mexican restaurant in downtown Sunnyvale serving authentic Mexican cuisine but what really stands out are the drinks. The margaritas are authentic, delicious, and unique. Plenty of outdoor seating on Castro Street.

[The Food]
The food here is great for a Mexican restaurant. Competition is tough in the Bay Area, but I would give them a 8/10 for the food. It tastes real, but a little lacking in uniqueness and flavor. However, still very good. The prices are fair for the Bay Area.

[The Drinks]
We frequently come here just for the drinks. They have Margaritas that don't taste watered down or artificial with a ton of sugar. I feel like they use real fruit, good tequila, and put care into their recipes. We were really impressed. They have these spicy margaritas which are amazing. One of them, they roast the Jalapeno's beforehand giving the drink a smoky flavor. The Guava Margarita is probably their best drink. Definitely worth stopping by and getting drunk here!

[The Location]
Location here is right on Castro Street in downtown Mountain View, near the train station. They have lots of outdoor seating, restrooms available for customers, and fast service. I never felt like I was too close to anyone, and the sunshine was really nice.

Overall, a good Mexican restaurant with an amazing bar. Probably the best margaritas in the South Bay. Worth a visit.<//text>

I usually am really generous with my reviews but I couldn't help but give a 1 star review to this restaurant because of so many reasons. I ordered Tacos De La Calle from Agave for pickup.
I looked at their Google menu and noticed that the cost for Tacos was $11 so I told my roommate to get me that (that was my mistake. I should have looked at the online menu on their website) and later found out that the cost of those 2 tacos was $18 + taxes.
Because of the whole covid situation, I understand the reasoning behind the price hike (if that is the case) and I am totally fine with it but what bothers me is the fact that the food was sub-par (it may even be the most expensive and worst tacos I have ever had). Both tacos just had dry meat and lettuce in it and nothing else (no salsa, guac, dressing) and the size of the tacos was really disappointing as well. It came with a side of really salty chips and really salty and bitter green sauce (chilli Verde I believe). There was also rice and beans but rice was uncooked for most part.

I will not be coming back after this experience.< /text>

Went on a Friday afternoon for lunch. I normally avoid Mexican cuisine, but decided to give it a shot and I am glad I did.
